#compdef craft sentry-craft
# =============================================================================
# craft — Sentry's "Universal Sentry release CLI" — a
#         TypeScript-Node CLI for release automation: version
#         bumping, changelog management, multi-target artifact
#         building, and publishing to npm + GitHub Releases +
#         Cargo + PyPI + Docker Hub + GitHub Container Registry
#         + Homebrew + Sentry's CDN + 20+ other distribution
#         targets.  Used by Sentry's own SDKs (JavaScript,
#         Python, Java, .NET, etc.) for synchronized cross-
#         language releases.
#         Distinguishing from semantic-release, lerna, changesets,
#         and other release tools by:
#           - 6 SUBCOMMANDS via yargs:
#               * prepare [NEW-VERSION]   — bump version files,
#                                            update changelog,
#                                            create release branch,
#                                            push to remote
#               * publish NEW-VERSION     — build + publish
#                                            artifacts to all
#                                            configured targets
#               * targets                 — list configured release
#                                            targets
#               * config                  — show resolved craft
#                                            config
#               * artifacts <subcommand>  — manage release-
#                                            artifact store
#               * changelog               — generate / validate
#                                            CHANGELOG.md
#           - 20+ RELEASE TARGETS — single .craft.yml lists all
#             distribution targets; supported targets include:
#               * npm                       (package publish)
#               * pypi                      (Python package)
#               * cargo                     (Rust crates.io)
#               * maven                     (Java/Kotlin Maven Central)
#               * docker                    (Docker Hub)
#               * gcr / ghcr                (GitHub / Google Container Registry)
#               * brew                      (Homebrew tap)
#               * github                    (GitHub Releases)
#               * gh-pages                  (GitHub Pages site)
#               * aws-lambda-layer          (AWS Lambda layers)
#               * gcs                       (Google Cloud Storage)
#               * commit-on-git-repository  (release-branch commits)
#               * registry                  (Sentry's release registry)
#               * upm                       (Unity package)
#               * sentry-pypi               (Sentry private PyPI)
#               * github-actions-marketplace
#               * crates                    (crates.io)
#               * symbol-collector          (Sentry symbol upload)
#             Each target receives the built artifacts +
#             credentials and runs its publish flow in parallel.
#           - MULTI-LANGUAGE ARTIFACT BUILDS — craft is language-
#             agnostic; it reads .craft.yml to determine which
#             build commands to invoke (`make`, `npm run build`,
#             `cargo build`, `python setup.py sdist`, etc.) and
#             then dispatches the resulting artifacts to the
#             configured targets
#           - DRY-RUN MODE via --dry-run — no file writes,
#             commits, pushes, or API mutations.  Test the
#             release flow safely.
#           - INTERACTIVE PROMPTS via `prompts` — `craft prepare`
#             asks for version-bump type (major / minor / patch /
#             custom) interactively when NEW-VERSION not
#             provided; --no-input suppresses (default in CI)
#           - CRAFT_* ENV VAR OVERRIDES — every flag has a
#             CRAFT_<FLAG> environment variable equivalent via
#             yargs `.env('CRAFT')`
#           - GLOBAL --log-level — Debug / Info / Warn / Error
#             via tiered logger
#           - SENTRY INSTRUMENTATION — craft instruments itself
#             with @sentry/node for telemetry on internal
#             Sentry release runs
#           - CALVER + SEMVER both supported — --calver-offset
#             for CalVer schemes; semver default
#           - GIT INTEGRATION via simple-git — automatic branch
#             creation (release/X.Y.Z), commit, push to remote
#             (--remote)
#           - ARTIFACT REUSE — `publish` can reuse already-built
#             artifacts from previous runs via the artifact store
#             (artifacts list/get/remove subcommands)
#           - AWS LAMBDA + GCS UPLOADS — built-in clients for
#             cloud artifact uploads (@aws-sdk/client-lambda +
#             @google-cloud/storage)
#         Used by: Sentry's own multi-SDK release flow (their
#         Python, JavaScript, Java, .NET, PHP, Ruby, Go, Rust,
#         Elixir, Native SDKs all use craft), security
#         engineering teams replicating Sentry's release
#         automation, and as a reference implementation of
#         `prompts` + yargs + simple-git + multi-target
#         artifact distribution in TypeScript-Node.
#
# Author:  Sentry (sentry.io) — application-monitoring SaaS.
#          craft maintained by Sentry's engineering team since
#          ~2018.  Current version 2.27.0-dev.  License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/getsentry/craft
#          https://github.com/getsentry/craft/blob/master/src/index.ts
#          https://github.com/getsentry/craft/blob/master/src/commands/prepare.ts
#          https://github.com/getsentry/craft/blob/master/src/commands/publish.ts
#          https://github.com/getsentry/craft/blob/master/package.json
# CLI:     src/index.ts — uses yargs (well-documented elsewhere).
#          Headline library: **prompts** (yargs is documented
#          across many Node completions; prompts is the new
#          variant being documented here, completing Axis 8
#          three-language symmetry across Rust / Go / TS-Node).
# Library: prompts (https://github.com/terkelg/prompts —
#          "Lightweight, beautiful and user-friendly interactive
#           prompts" — Terkel Gjervig Hansen.  Distinct from
#           dialoguer (R661, Rust Axis 8 opener) and c-bata/
#           go-prompt (R662, Go Axis 8 expansion) by being:
#              1. SINGLE-FUNCTION API — prompts is invoked as
#                 ONE function call accepting an array of
#                 question objects:
#                   import prompts from 'prompts';
#                   const { name, age, color } = await prompts([
#                     { type: 'text',    name: 'name',  message: "What's your name?" },
#                     { type: 'number',  name: 'age',   message: 'Age?' },
#                     { type: 'select',  name: 'color', message: 'Favorite color?',
#                       choices: [
#                         { title: 'Red',   value: '#f00' },
#                         { title: 'Green', value: '#0f0' },
#                         { title: 'Blue',  value: '#00f' },
#                       ]
#                     },
#                   ]);
#                 Distinct from Inquirer's chainable .prompt()
#                 builder + dialoguer's per-prompt struct +
#                 go-prompt's REPL framework.
#              2. 11 PROMPT TYPES — text / password / invisible
#                 / number / confirm / list / toggle / select /
#                 multiselect / autocomplete / autocompleteMultiselect
#                 / date.  Covers all common interactive needs.
#              3. ZERO RUNTIME DEPENDENCIES — terkelg/prompts has
#                 NO production npm dependencies (minimal devDeps
#                 only).  Bundle size <20KB minified.  Distinct
#                 from Inquirer.js which has 8+ runtime deps,
#                 and Enquirer's larger footprint.
#              4. DECLARATIVE QUESTION OBJECTS — each prompt is
#                 a plain JS object with `type`, `name`, `message`,
#                 `initial`, `validate`, `format`, `onState`,
#                 `onSubmit`, `onCancel` properties.  No builder
#                 pattern; no chaining.  Simple JSON-style
#                 configuration.
#              5. INITIAL VALUES + VALIDATE + FORMAT — every
#                 prompt accepts:
#                   * initial: default value (or function
#                     producing one based on previous answers)
#                   * validate: (value) => true | string error
#                   * format: (value) => transformed value
#                   * onState: (state) => observe keystroke
#                     events
#                 Distinct from Inquirer's separate validate vs
#                 transformer separation.
#              6. AUTOCOMPLETE TYPES — autocomplete + auto
#                 completeMultiselect with custom suggest
#                 functions for filtering large lists; Inquirer
#                 needs the inquirer-autocomplete-prompt plugin;
#                 dialoguer has FuzzySelect; prompts has it
#                 built-in.
#              7. ASYNC SUPPORT — all callbacks can be async;
#                 dynamic prompt arrays via async functions:
#                   await prompts(async (prev) => buildQuestions(prev))
#              8. CONDITIONAL PROMPTS via `type: prev => ...`
#                 — a prompt's type can be a function of previous
#                 answers, returning the actual type string OR
#                 `null` to skip:
#                   { type: prev => prev > 10 ? 'text' : null,
#                     name: 'over10', message: '...' }
#              9. CTRL-C HANDLING via onCancel callback —
#                 explicit hook for user cancellation; default
#                 sets value to undefined.
#             10. TERKEL-GJERVIG / SOLO-MAINTAINED PROVENANCE —
#                 Terkel Gjervig Hansen is a Danish independent
#                 developer; prompts is solo-maintained and
#                 has stayed minimalist since its 2018 release.
#                 Used by Vite, create-react-app, npm itself,
#                 yarn, gatsby, ng (Angular CLI), Vue CLI, and
#                 hundreds of other major tools.)
# License: MIT (prompts); MIT (craft)
# Status:  prompts — 9,280+ stars on terkelg/prompts, ~90M weekly
#          npm downloads (TOP-20 npm package by downloads);
#          foundational interactive-prompt library used by:
#            * Vite (init wizard)
#            * create-react-app (project options)
#            * npm CLI (init prompts in some flows)
#            * yarn CLI (init + workspaces prompts)
#            * Gatsby (gatsby new prompts)
#            * Angular CLI (ng new prompts)
#            * Vue CLI (vue create prompts)
#            * Astro (astro create prompts)
#            * SvelteKit (npm create svelte prompts)
#            * Remix (npx create-remix prompts)
#            * Next.js (create-next-app prompts)
#            * @sentry/craft (THIS — release CLI prompts)
#            * 50,000+ npm packages
#          craft — 182+ stars on getsentry/craft, used by all
#          Sentry SDKs for synchronized cross-language releases.
#
